UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199692900099
AB  - This paper addresses the concern that strategic trade policy will inevitably invite retaliation by presenting examples in which tariffs and export taxes/subsidies can improve the welfare of importing and exporting nations at the same time. We argue that retaliation is less likely in such cases. The conditions required for these results depend upon the relative sizes of the markets in the trading countries, the number of firms in each, and the shape of market demand and cost functions.
